# combine flights and planes data
flights_planes <- flights %>% 
  left_join(planes, "tailnum") %>%  
  filter(origin == "EWR") %>% 
  mutate(across(where(is.character), ~as_factor(.x))) %>%
  drop_na()


model1_base_data <- flights_planes %>% 
  left_join(weather, c("time_hour", "origin")) %>%
  left_join(additional_weather, c("time_hour" = "datetime")) %>%
  left_join(daily_weather, c("date", "origin")) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  select(-time_hour, -origin, -dest, -dep_delay, -wind_gust, -tailnum, -seats,
         -manufacturer, -wind_dir, -date)

Dealing with missing values

It is assumed that the weather between the 3 NY airports are similar so any missing values for: - wind_dir (wind direction) - wind_speed - wind_gust - visib

Will be replaced by the average of the other airports data for that date.

Average Delay Length

Average departure delay at Newark is approximately 48.6mins compared to 48.6mins at JFK (the same) and 50.7mins at LGA. However, the median delay time is quite a bit higher at Newark at 26mins, compared to 22 and 23 for JFK and LGA, respectively.

The average monthly delay duration peaks in the summer in July, showing a strong seasonal variation. However, the number of flight delays stays high from March to August (~4000 delayed flights per month). This tells us that despite July not being the month with the most delays, there must be something else which is causing the delays to be on average, longer in this month. For example, there is a significant spike in the number of delays in December and January however the average delay durations are at an annual low (around 43mins) compared to the peak in July of 62 mins.

Annual Wind Data

Define maximum deviance between wind direction and closest angle of runway. Sign of difference doesn’t matter.

Wind magnitude creates a score = max_wind_dev * wind_speed


wind_deviance_mag <- weather %>% 
  group_by(time_hour, origin) %>% 
  mutate(min_wind_dev = if_else(origin == "EWR", 
                            min(abs(wind_dir - 40),
                                abs(wind_dir - (360 + 40)), # 40 degrees
                                abs(wind_dir - 220),
                                abs(wind_dir - 290), 
                                abs(wind_dir - 110)),
                            min(abs(wind_dir - 40),
                                abs(wind_dir - (360 + 40)), # 40 degrees
                                abs(wind_dir - 220),
                                abs(wind_dir - 310), 
                                abs(wind_dir - 130))),
         wind_magnitude = wind_speed * min_wind_dev) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  select(time_hour, origin, wind_magnitude)

# LGA
weather %>%
  filter(origin == "LGA") %>% 
  filter(wind_speed != 0, wind_dir != 0) %>% 
  mutate(beaufort = case_when(
    wind_speed <= 3 ~ 1,
    wind_speed <= 7 ~ 2,
    wind_speed <= 12 ~ 3,
    wind_speed <= 18 ~ 4,
    wind_speed <= 24 ~ 5,
    wind_speed <= 31 ~ 6,
    wind_speed <= 38 ~ 7,
    wind_speed <= 46 ~ 8
  ),
  beaufort = factor(beaufort, levels = c(8,7,6,5,4,3,2,1), ordered = TRUE)) %>% 
  group_by(wind_dir, beaufort) %>% 
  summarise(count = n()) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = wind_dir, y = count, fill = beaufort)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_polar() +
  scale_x_continuous(n.breaks = 12) +
  labs(title = "Windrose - Wind speed and direction",
       subtitle = "JFK",
       x = "",
       y = "",
       fill = "Beaufort Scale") +
  theme(panel.background = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.major.y = element_line(colour = "grey", size = 0.1),
        axis.text.x = element_text(vjust = 1, colour = "black"),
        axis.text.y = element_blank(),
        axis.ticks = element_blank()) +
    # add runway 4 (40 degrees)
  geom_vline(xintercept = 40, col = "red", size = 3, alpha = 0.5) + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = 220, col = "red", size = 3, alpha = 0.5) +
  # add Newark runway 31 (310 degrees)
  geom_vline(xintercept = 310, col = "red", size = 3, alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = 130, col = "red", size = 3, alpha = 0.5)
